<DOC><DOCNO> AP890425-0241 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-89 0155EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights    04-25 0877</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, </SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines would slash its workforce by 43percent from pre-strike levels and raise $1.8 billion from assetsales under a new business plan presented to the airline'screditors.   The proposal, which must be approved by creditors and a federalbankruptcy judge, calls for Eastern to reduce its fleet size to 157aircraft from 255 and the number of cities served to 77 from apre-strike 102.   Eastern President Phil Bakes on Monday would not specify all thecities where Eastern would cut service, but said the company wouldsell its Philadelphia hub, a total of 117 unspecified airport gatesand 28 landing slots, and de-emphasize some foreign routes.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Exxon Corp.'s first-quarter earnings fell 13percent as rising crude oil prices took a bite out of refiningmargins and the Alaskan oil spill took a toll mostly on thecompany's image.   For the three months ended March 31, earnings at the nation'sbiggest oil company declined to $1.3 billion, or 99 cents a share,from $1.5 billion, or $1.06 a share, in the first quarter of lastyear. Revenue rose 1 percent to $22.2 billion compared with $22billion in the 1988 period, Exxon said Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United States and the European EconomicCommunity are near an agreement in their dispute over an EEC ban onimports of U.S. beef treated with growth-boosting hormones, a Dutchofficial said.   U.S. officials have agreed to let the EEC certify U.S. beef dueto be exported to the EEC as having been raised without the use ofhormones, Dutch Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs Yvonne vanRooy said Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   NCNB Inc. said it has dropped its $2.4billion bid to acquire Citizens andamp; Southern Corp. because theAtlanta bank refused to discuss the proposal.   The Charlotte, N.C., banking company launched the takeover bidlast month. It was promptly rejected by the Candamp;S board, which turneddown appeals by NCNB Chairman Hugh L. McColl to negotiate a newdeal. McColl withdrew the offer in a statement Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita announced today hewill resign to take responsibility for a massive influence-peddlingscandal involving stock trading that he said has led to growingpublic distrust of politicians.   The scandal and a widely criticized sales tax that took effectApril 1 sent his popularity rating skidding to a rock-bottom 3.9percent and made him Japan's most unpopular prime minister sinceWorld War II.   Takeshita, 65, spoke at a nationally televised news conferenceafter telling a Cabinet meeting he would end his 18-month tenure inoffice, half of it a downhill slide due to a scandal named afterthe Recruit Co. conglomerate.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court has refused to intervene inthe controversy over Alar, rejecting attempts to revive a lawsuitby Ralph Nader and others aimed at banning use of the chemical onapples.   The suit, which the justices let die Monday without comment, hadsought to force the Environmental Protection Agency to immediatelyban Alar, used primarily to enhance apples' color, ripening andshelf life.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court has left intact a $101million refund some of the nation's telephone companies wereordered to pay customers for excessive charges in 1978.   The court, without comment, Monday rejected arguments that theFederal Communications Commission overstepped its authority inordering the refunds.   The commission in 1976 allowed American Telephone andamp; TelegraphCo. to set phone rates designed to yield a rate of return of up to10 percent a year. ATandamp;T's earnings in 1978 exceeded the 10 percentfigure by $101 million, the commission ruled in 1984.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Swiss drug manufacturing giant F.Hoffmann-La Roche andamp; Co. Inc. said it will modernize its sharestructure and reorganize its corporate framework.   The changes announced Monday would make it easier to invest inthe company and conform to pending changes in Swiss corporate law.Hoffmann-La Roche failed in a takeover bid for Sterling Drug Inc.last year, and the streamlining could help the company in otherU.S. takeover attempts, some analysts said. The company's U.S. armis based in Nutley, N.J.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   First Boston Corp. is reducing its staff byabout 200 employees in the latest cutback by Wall Street firmsattributed to a weak securities market.   The nation's sixth largest investment firm said Monday thereductions were being made this week through a combination ofattrition, voluntary departures and layoffs. Spokeswoman MonicaPrihoda declined to say how many people were being fired or fromwhich departments the cuts were being made.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   Stock prices posted spotty losses Monday as traders cashed insome of the market's recent gains. The Dow Jones industrialaverage, up 72.40 points last week, slipped 6.78 to 2,402.68.   The dollar drifted higher against most major currencies.   Bond prices finished little changed.   Weekend showers in one of the driest parts of the Corn Belttriggered a steep sell-off of corn and soybean futures; oats closedlower; wheat futures gained slightly; energy futures plunged;precious metals advanced; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>